Team: Kerui Geng (Graduate student)

Project: Predicting consumers' following number of purchases based on their reviews and item characteristics

Github link: https://keruigeng.github.io (This link is a link to the github.io site); https://github.com/keruigeng/keruigeng.github.io/tree/master (This link is a link where you can find all the data, data are in the master branch)

Introduction¶

My plan is to use the combined dataset to predict consumers' future purchasing quantity based on their one-time purchase information. To achieve this, I take four main steps:

  1. I combine product-level datasets from amazon with manufacturer datasets from People Data Lab.
  2. I cleaned the previous combined data. To get the numerical aspect of the item characteristic, I subtract numerical information from string variables and split the category-subcategory variable into a set of categorical variables.
  3. I analyze the data and find out the correlation between item characteristics and consumer's review rating with future purchasing quantiles. I also plot the consumer's future purchasing quantiles versus some item characteristics and consumer's review rating to explore their non-linear relationship.
  4. I train a linear regression to explore whether consumer review can predict future purchasing quantiles. I also train a K-nearest neighborhood model and look at their test performance with consumer's review and without consumer's review indicators. To better predict the consumers' following number of purchases, I choose the random forest model as my prediction model and predict the future purchasing quantities bought.

In marketing, a good shopping experience here, measured based on a consumer's review rating, would boost consumers' trust in the seller, thus stimulating more purchases. In economics, some products are complementary, meaning consumers gain more utility if they consume several products together. Therefore, some item characteristics might predict the consumers' following purchasing quantity. In sum, my project mainly deals with those two questions:

  • (1): Do consumer's review ratings predict their following purchasing quantity?
  • (2): Can consumer's review rating and item characteristics predict consumers' following number of purchases well?

Hopefully, this project shield light on the importance of consumer review in predicting their future purchasing quantities. In addition, this project tries to create a system that can help online sellers predict consumers' future purchasing quantities. Understanding consumers' future purchasing quantities can help sellers adjust their goods in stock and change their marketing strategy. Those are important for the seller's total sales and potentially boost seller profits.

The following code will import the libraries that I will use throughout this project.

Extraction, Transform, and Load (ETL)¶

Product Data:

The data is downloaded from data.world. This open and free platform provides rich data to the public. I download the Fashion products on Amazon.com from this platform (https://data.world/promptcloud/fashion-products-on-amazon-com). Fashion products on Amazon.com is a pre-crawled dataset, taken as a subset of a larger dataset (more than 7 million fashion products) created by extracting data from Amazon.

This dataset contains consumer-product level purchasing information. There are two sets of features. One set is the consumer's review rating, including the average review rating, the consumer's own review rating after purchasing, the gap between the consumer's own review rating and average review rating, and the number of reviews. The set of features is item characteristics, including the item price, category, manufacturer, number available in stock, etc. For labels, it tracks the consumers' other purchasing quantities after reviewing or buying this item. This data is beneficial for my project questions. It contains a rich set of product information for every purchase. Meanwhile, it tracks this consumer's other purchasing behavior after buying or viewing this product. This can help predict consumers' following purchasing behavior based on their current buying information.

Manufacturer Data:

The manufacturer data is downloaded from People Data Lab. The data can be accessed here: https://pdl.ai/3Jh6dCb. This dataset contains manufacturer information for the global companies, including company country, industry, et al. This data can be merged with product-level data to obtain more manufacturer information, such as their location, year founded, and company size.

Cleaning the product Data

Now the product data is ready. The next step is to clean the data. This includes getting numerical information from string variables, splitting the category-subcategory variable into a set of category variables, dropping the unnecessary variables, and dealing with missing data.

The first thing I should do is get numerical information from string variables. For example, string 9.99 can be extracted as a numerical value 9.99. Variables, "price", "number_available_in_stock", 'average_review_rating' and 'customer_review', are strings. I will get the numerical element of those variables. I create a new variable, customer review gap, which is the difference between customer_review and average_review_rating. For labels, I get the number of items bought after buying or viewing this product from two string labels.

In [ ]:
product=product_df.copy()
#Iterm characteristics, "price", "number_available_in_stock" are string. I need the numerical element of those varibale.
product['price']=pd.to_numeric(product['price'].str.replace('',''),errors='coerce')
product['number_available_in_stock']=product.number_available_in_stock.str.replace('new','')
product['number_available_in_stock']=product.number_available_in_stock.str.replace('used','')
product['number_available_in_stock']=pd.to_numeric(product['number_available_in_stock'].str.strip(),errors='coerce')
In [ ]:
#Geting Consumer review rating numerical value from Consumer review string variables
product['average_review_rating']=pd.to_numeric(product.average_review_rating.str.replace('out of 5 stars','').str.strip())
product=product[-product['customer_reviews'].str.split('//').isna()]
product['customer_review']=0
a=product['customer_reviews'].str.split('//')
for i in range(len(a)):
  product['customer_review'][i]=a.iloc[i][1]
product['customer_review']=pd.to_numeric(product['customer_review'],errors='coerce') 
product['customer review gap']=product['customer_review']-product['average_review_rating']
In [ ]:
#For labels, I get the quantity of items bought after buying or viewing this product from the followung two string labels.
product['Number of items bought after buying this item']=product.customers_who_bought_this_item_also_bought.str.count('http://www.amazon').fillna(0)
product['Number of items bought after viewing this item']=product.items_customers_buy_after_viewing_this_item.str.count('http://www.amazon').fillna(0)

The second thing I do is to split the category-subcategory variable into a set of category variables. "amazon_category_and_sub_category" is a string that denotes the categories and subcategories of items. There are multiple subcategories for one product. To model the impact of each subcategory, I transform this variable into a set of categorical variables.

In [ ]:
product[['category','sub_category_1','sub_category_2','sub_category_3','sub_category_4']]=product.amazon_category_and_sub_category.str.split('>', expand=True)
product[['category','sub_category_1','sub_category_2','sub_category_3','sub_category_4']]

The third thing I do is to drop the unnecessary variables. Item 'uniq_id','product_name', 'sellers', 'amazon_category_and_sub_category', 'customers_who_bought_this_item_also_bought', 'description', 'product_information', 'product_description','items_customers_buy_after_viewing_this_item', 'customer_questions_and_answers','customer_reviews' are the information that is hard to quantify. I didn't need them to predict the consumer's following purchasing quantity. Therefore, I drop them here.

In [ ]:
columns_to_drop=['uniq_id','product_name','sellers','amazon_category_and_sub_category','customers_who_bought_this_item_also_bought','description','product_information', 'product_description', 'items_customers_buy_after_viewing_this_item', 'customer_questions_and_answers','customer_reviews']
product=product.drop(columns_to_drop,axis=1)

The last thing I do is dealing with missing data. For quantitive variable, fill the missing value with variable mean. For qualatitive variable, fill the missing value with variable 0.

In [ ]:
###For quantitive variable, fill the missing value with variable mean
product.fillna(product.mean(),inplace=True)
###For qualatitive variable, fill the missing value with variable 0
product.fillna(0,inplace=True)

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

With the clean and tiny data, I can start to look at what it tells. This can be done in several steps. Firstly, I will look at the description of numerical variables, which gives us basic distribution information about my data. Then I look at the distribution of the following purchasing quantity. Next, I will examine the correlation between consumer review ratings and some important item characteristics with the following purchasing quantity. Lastly, I will use line plots of labels with respect to some features to show their non-linear relationship.

Firstly, check the distributions of numerical variables

In [ ]:
##Look the basic information of numerical variable:range, mean and counts. Pay attention to extreme values. They might make no sense

Secondly, look at the distribution of the labels I am interested in. There are two labels I am interested in. One is number of items bought after buying this item. The other is number of items bought after viewing this item. I check the number of items for each purchasing quantity and use the histograms to show their distributions.

In [ ]:

For consumer review, 'average_review_rating' has a high and negative correlation with labels. 'number_of_reviews' and 'customer review gap' have positive but smaller correlations with labels. In [ ]:
#There are too many observations and highly non-linear relationshp. Therefore, I use the mean of labels for a certain range of number available in stock to smooth the line.
#The following three line codes calculate the average number of items bought for a 4 width interval.
product['number_available_in_stock_1']=round(product['number_available_in_stock']/3)*3
y_1=product.groupby('number_available_in_stock_1')['Number of items bought after buying this item'].mean()
y_2=product.groupby('number_available_in_stock_1')['Number of items bought after viewing this item'].mean()

product=product.drop('number_available_in_stock_1',axis=1)
x_1=pd.Series(y_1.index)
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (11,6)
plt.plot(x_1, y_1, 'r-')
plt.xlabel('Number available in stock')
plt.ylabel('Number of items bought')
plt.plot(x_1, y_2, 'g-')
plt.ylim(0,8)
plt.legend(["Number of items bought after buying this item", "Number of items bought after viewing this item"])
Out[ ]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x7f1242c39350>

The above figures show that consumers bought more products after buying an item for the same number available in stock compared with that viewing an item. In addition, as "number_available_in_stock" increases, the number of items customers bought increases. But their relationship is not strictly linear. Therefore, the non-linear machine learning algorithm might work well in modeling their relationship.

Model Fitting and Prediction¶

I will train different models to explore my two project questions in this part. To analyze the first question (Do consumer review ratings predict their following purchasing quantity?), I will take the next two steps. Firstly, I will train a linear regression to test whether consumers' review rating matters for predicting the following purchasing quantities. Secondly, I will train a K-nearest neighbor (KNN) model to see whether including the consumer's review rating will affect the prediction score.

Besides, I will explore the second question: Can consumer review ratings and item characteristics predict consumers' following number of purchases well? Firstly, I train a KNN model using and calculating its prediction performance. Next, I train a random forest regression model to calculate its prediction performance. Lastly, based on the performance of those two models, I choose one that achieves the best performance and plots the predicted labels versus actual labels.

The previous results show that none of the review indicators(number_of_reviews,average_review_rating,customer_review, customer review gap) can significantly predict the purchasing quantities. It indicates that consumer reviews don't affect customers' future purchasing quantities.

Secondly, I will train a K-nearest neighbor model to see whether including the consumer's review rating or not will affect the prediction score. In the following cell, I will train a KNN model using all product features but excluding consumer review indicators.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsRegressor
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
#get the features without consumer review and transform the categorical vaariables into a set of dummies.
X_selected_drop_review=product.drop(['Number of items bought after buying this item','Number of items bought after viewing this item','number_of_reviews','average_review_rating','customer_review', 'customer review gap'],axis=1)
#Transform the categorical variable into dummies.
X_drop_review=pd.get_dummies(X_selected_drop_review)
X1_train_drop_review,X1_test_drop_review,y1_train_drop_review,y1_test_drop_review=train_test_split(X_drop_review,y1,test_size=0.2,random_state=42)
X2_train_drop_review,X2_test_drop_review,y2_train_drop_review,y2_test_drop_review=train_test_split(X_drop_review,y2,test_size=0.2,random_state=42)


#Since I only want to test the importance of consumer's review, the key point is to see the model's prediction performace with consumer's review and without consumer's review.
#Therefore,  I set k=10 here
knn_reg=KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=10)
knn_reg.fit(X1_train_drop_review,y1_train_drop_review)
y1_test_pred=knn_reg.predict(X1_test_drop_review)
mse=mean_squared_error(y1_test_drop_review,y1_test_pred)
rmse=np.sqrt(mse)
print(f'The mse of knn model without consumer review for number of items bought after buying this item is {rmse}')
knn_reg.fit(X2_train_drop_review,y2_train_drop_review)
y2_test_pred=knn_reg.predict(X2_test_drop_review)
mse=mean_squared_error(y2_test_drop_review,y2_test_pred)
rmse=np.sqrt(mse)
print(f'The mse of knn model without consumer review for number of items bought after viewing this item is {rmse}')

The mse of knn model with consumer review for number of items bought after buying this item is 1.9517275372884646
The mse of knn model with consumer review for number of items bought after viewing this item is 1.697886507015309

The above results indicate that adding a consumer's review indeed decreases the test root mean squared error(rmse). Adding consumer reviews decreases the rmse of the number of items bought after buying this item by 5.52%. Adding consumer reviews decreases the rmse of the number of items bought after viewing this item by 3.36%. Even though the review coefficients are not significant in the linear model, the KNN model that can capture the non-linear relationships indicates that a consumer's review can contribute to predicting the consumer's following purchasing quantities.

Question 2. I will explore the second question: Can consumer review ratings and item characteristics predict consumers' following number of purchases well? Firstly, I train a KNN model using and calculating its prediction performance.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsRegressor
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
RMSE_knn=[]
for k in range(1,100,5):
  knn_reg=KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=k)
  score1=cross_val_score(knn_reg,X1_train,y1_train,cv=3,scoring='neg_mean_squared_error',n_jobs=-1).mean()
  score2=cross_val_score(knn_reg,X2_train,y2_train,cv=3,scoring='neg_mean_squared_error',n_jobs=-1).mean()
  RMSE_knn.append([k,np.sqrt(-score1),np.sqrt(-score2)])

Next, I train a random forest regression model to calculate its cross-validation performance.

In [ ]:
RMSE_tree=[]
n_estimators=[5,10,20,50,100]
max_depths=[1,5,10,50,100]
for n in n_estimators:
  for d in max_depths:
    rnd_reg=RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=n,max_depth=d,random_state=42,n_jobs=-1)
    score1=cross_val_score(rnd_reg,X1_train,y1_train,cv=3,scoring='neg_mean_squared_error').mean()
    score2=cross_val_score(rnd_reg,X2_train,y2_train,cv=3,scoring='neg_mean_squared_error').mean()
    RMSE_tree.append([n,d,np.sqrt(-score1),np.sqrt(-score2)])

In [ ]:
data_new=pd.DataFrame(X1_test,columns=X1_test.columns,index=y1_test.index)
data_new['y1_test']=y1_test
data_new['y1_test_pred']=pd.Series(y1_test_pred)
data_new['y2_test']=y2_test
data_new['y2_test_pred']=pd.Series(y2_test_pred)

data_new['number_available_in_stock_1']=round(data_new['number_available_in_stock']/3)*3
y_1=data_new.groupby('number_available_in_stock_1')['y1_test'].mean()
y_2=data_new.groupby('number_available_in_stock_1')['y1_test_pred'].mean()
y_3=data_new.groupby('number_available_in_stock_1')['y2_test'].mean()
y_4=data_new.groupby('number_available_in_stock_1')['y2_test_pred'].mean()

x_1=pd.Series(y_1.index)
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (11,6)
plt.plot(x_1, y_1, 'r-')
plt.plot(x_1, y_2, 'g-')
plt.plot(x_1, y_3, 'y-')
plt.plot(x_1, y_4, 'b-')
plt.xlabel('Number available in stock')
plt.ylabel('Number of items bought')
plt.ylim(0,10)
plt.legend(["True Number of items bought after buying this product", "Predicted Number of items bought after buying this product","True Number of items bought after viewing this product", "Predicted Number of items bought after viewing this product"])
Out[ ]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x7f122eb56e10>

The above figure plots the true number of items bought versus the predicted amounts of the item bought. Red and green lines represent the number of items bought after purchasing this product. Yellow and blue lines represent the number of items bought after viewing this product. The average root means squared errors are 1.79 and 1.56, respectively. The predictions are ok when the number available is smaller than 30. However, the results could be better when the number available is larger than 35. One possible reason is the consumer's future purchasing behaviors are so complex. Future economic conditions and preferences may influence it, and many factors that my model needs to capture. More indicators, especially consumer characteristics, can be collected to achieve better prediction.

Conlusions¶

This project mainly deals with two questions for consumers' future purchasing behaviors.

The first one is: Do consumers' review ratings predict their following purchasing quantity? Based on the linear regression model, no significant coefficients are found. However, the linear regression model can only capture the linear relationship of features with labels. To capture the non-linear relationship, I train a K-nearest neighborhood model and look at their test performance with the consumer's review and without the consumer's review indicators. Adding consumer review indicators decreases test rooted mean squared error for the number of items bought after buying this product by 5.52%. It reduces test rooted mean squared error for the number of items purchased after viewing this product by 3.36%. This indicates that consumer review indeed can contribute to predicting their following purchasing quantities.

The second one is: Can consumer review ratings and item characteristics predict consumers' following number of purchases well? To better predict the consumers' following number of purchases, I use the cross-validation method to choose the best parameters of the K-nearest neighborhood model and random forest model. After getting the best parameter, I calculate each model's prediction rooted mean squared errors. The rooted mean squared error for the K-nearest neighborhood model is 1.8973387681505385 for the number of items bought after buying this product and 1.664352490838144 for the number of items purchased after viewing this product. The rooted mean squared error for the random forest model is 1.7924393033729449 for the number of items bought after buying this product and 1.5625982325557126 for the number of items purchased after viewing this product. Generally, the rooted mean squared errors for the random forest model are smaller than the K-nearest neighborhood model. Therefore, I choose the random forest model as my prediction model and predict the future purchasing quantities bought. The prediction results are ok but could be better. One possible reason is the consumer's future purchasing behaviors are so complex. Future economic conditions and preferences may influence it, and many factors that my model needs to capture. More indicators, especially consumer characteristics, can be collected to achieve better prediction.

The first link tries to predict outfit compatibility and retrieve complementary items from the set dataset I use. The second is to develop a system to recommend product size fits {Small, Fit, Large} to customers. I hope this tutorial is helpful for understanding consumer behaviors.

Link 2: https://www.amazon.science/publications/recommending-product-sizes-to-customers

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb

            which will convert mynotebook.ipynb to the default format (probably HTML).

            You can specify the export format with `--to`.
            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'rst', 'script', 'slides'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic' and 'full'. You
            can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template basic mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of 
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.
